@node installation "Installing MOSNet"

 MOSNet is a modular program and it comes in a form of several archives:

 MOSNet-Base      - core components: kernel, miami.library, syslog viewer and control panel.
 MOSNet-Usergroup - usergroup.library. This library is a compatilibity layer for some
                    software ported from UNIX and depending on multiuser environment (usually
                    servers). This library actually does not introduce any access control,
                    it just provides an access to group and passwd files and emulates
                    process ownership changing. A little amount of native Amiga software also
                    requires this library. The largest dependency is ixemul.library - a POSIX
                    API implementation for Amiga systems. Without usergroup.library it will not
                    recognise MOSNet and networked software which works under ixemul.library
                    will fail. So it's recommended to install usergroup.library for now. However
                    the next release of usergroup.library for m68k will not suffer from this
                    drawback.
 MOSNet-Server    - currently this package includes a DHCP server. For now it is in alpha stage
                    due to lack of demand, noone has even tested it.
 MOSNet-SDK       - this is a software developer kit which is needed for any programmer who wants
                    to develop networked software. Standard MorphOS SDK already contains most of
                    needed things, however this package contains newer version of several files
                    which will allow to use features not availible with original MorphOS SDK.

 Also a source code for all components is supplied.

 Installation of any component is very easy. Just unarchive it and run "Install" script. It will
require an Installer, currently it's availible only in m68k version. SDK doesn't have the installer
script, you'll just need to unpack it to your GG: directory (root of the GeekGadgets environment).

@endnode
@node configuration "MOSNet Configuration"

 MOSNet configuration is stored in text files in db directory. Since MOSNet kernel is derived from BSD
operating systems family the configuration is almost the same as any UNIX host configuration. You may
consult any UNIX administration literature for more details and tutorials about how the whole thing
works.

 Coniguration overview:

 @{"Beginners step-by-step HOW-TO" link config-beginners}
 @{"Using dynamic configuration (DHCP protocol)" link dhcp}
 @{"Using MiamiDeluxe control panels" link control-panels}
 @{"Using service scripts" link service-scripts}

 Configuration files in details:

 * Main configuration files:

 @{"general.config" link config-general}
 @{"netdb" link config-netdb}

 * Other standard configuration files:

 @{"interfaces" link config-interfaces}
 @{"hosts" link config-hosts}
 @{"networks" link config-networks}
 @{"protocols" link config-protocols}
 @{"services" link config-services}
 @{"static-routes" link config-routes}
 @{"resolv.conf" link config-resolver}
 @{"inet.access" link config-firewall}

@endnode
@node config-beginners "Beginners configuration HOW-TO"

 In this section a simple installation is explained. It assumes that your machine is a single host
or is on a small local network which connects to the Internet. There are two cases: static and dynamic
configuration. Static means that your network parameters (IP addresses, gateways, etc) are known and
permanent. Dynamic means that the network is configured by a special server called DHCP server. In this
case you don't need to know any network parameters at all, they will be supplied to you by this server
every time you connect to the network.

 If you don't know your configuration type, ask your network's system administrator or Internet provider.

 In case of static configuration you need to know the following:

 1. IP address of your machine.
 2. Your netmask.
 3. Default gateway IP address.
 4. DNS servers IP addresses.

 The following is optional:

 5. Your hostname.
 6. Your local domain names.

 If the network is your own then you know all this. Otherwise ask your system administrator.

 If you don't get a hostname then just invent it. Do not invent nonexisting local domains!

 After this you may proceed to setting up your machine.

 1. Using any text editor, edit @{"MOSNet/db/interfaces" link config-interfaces} file. Specify your
    IP address and netmask there in case of static configuration. Otherwise specify IP=DHCP and omit
    NETMASK parameter there. Don't forget UP keyword if you want this interface to go online
    automatically upon MOSNet startup.

    Example:

    eth0 DEV=DEVS:networks/via_rhinepci.device UNIT=0 IP=192.168.0.1 NETMASK=255.255.255.0 UP

 2. Edit @{"MOSNet/db/static-routes" link config-routes} file. For static configuration specify
    your default gateway there. For dynamic one remove or comment out everything from it! This
    is not strictly necessary however is highly recommended.

    Example:

    DEFAULT GATEWAY 128.32.5.16

 3. Edit @{"MOSNet/db/resolv.conf" link config-resolver} file. Place your DNS servers and local domain names (if there
    are any) there if your configuration is static. Remove any other sample entries from there, be sure that no nonexisting
    names and/or addresses are left there. This means that if your configuration is completely dynamic,
    this file must be empty!!! Information obtained from the DHCP server does not override this file, it is
    merged to its contents.

    Nonexistant domain names and DNS addresses cause significant performance drop and may even cause
    incorrect operation of the stack!!!

    Example:

    NAMESERVER 128.32.5.17
    NAMESERVER 128.32.5.20

 4. Edit @{"MOSNet/db/hosts" link config-hosts} file. There should be a line there which specifies that your
    interface's IP address is corresponding to your hostname. For example:

    192.168.0.1 mypegasos

    If your configuration is dynamic, remove everything from there except the definition of 127.0.0.1 address!

 5. Edit @{"MOSNet/db/general.config" link config-general} file. Find a HOSTNAME parameter there and place your
    hostname there. If your configuration is dynamic, don't erase it and invent something like "mypegasos". Usually
    this gets overriden by the DHCP protocol. You can also @{"set up a control panel" link control-panels} in
    this file if you want to. By default @{"MUI.MiamiPanel" link MUI.MiamiPanel.guide/Main} is used.

 This is all, you're ready to run MOSNet.

 If you want to know more, you can read other sections of this manual explaining the configuration in details.
You can also read some good books about networking administration and UNIX systems.

@endnode
@node dhcp "Using DHCP protocol"

 MOSNet comes with complete integrated DHCP protocol implementation. It allows you to avoid
specifying your interfaces configuration.
 To enable DHCP protocol for an interface use "DHCP" magic value for its IP address in the
@{"interface configuration record" link config-interfaces}, for example:

eth0 DEV=DEVS:networks/via_rhinepci.device UNIT=0 IP=DHCP UP

 Every time the interface is brought up a DHCP client process is started for it. Do not interrupt
this process manualy or you can lose your connection. DHCP client is running continuously until
the interface goes offline, maintaining the connection.

 The following information is retrieved by the DHCP (not everything can be present, this depends on
your DHCP server configuration):

 - IP address and netmask for the interface;
 - your default gateway;
 - your local host name;
 - your local domain names;
 - DNS servers addresses.

 Default gateway and host name override your configuration files. Other information (domain names
and DNS addresses) is appended to the statically configured data, your @{"network database" link config-netdb} is not
overriden. This allows you to add for example your own caching nameserver or your local network domain to the
configuration and these definitions will still work while you're connected to the Internet. However don't forget
to set up appropriate @{"routing" link config-routes} for your local network in this case since your default
gateway address will be changed.

 Data retrieved by the DHCP are not written to the configuration files. They are maintained only in memory and
are reset when the interface goes offline. Host name and default gateway settings stay until next DHCP query
(when the interface is brought online again).

 DHCP client stores two files in MOSNet:db directory: configuration file and leases database. The configuration
file contains some advanced settings and is normally absent.

 Do not run dhclient manually if you're not a networking expert and don't clearly understand how it works!
This will affect all your network connections. The client is normally started by MOSNet itself when an
interface with dynamic configuration is brought online.

 Here comes a complete documentation on these components:

 @{"dhclient" link dhclient.doc/Main}        - DHCP client
 @{"dhclient.conf" link dhclient.conf.doc/Main}   - DHCP client configuration file
 @{"dhclient.leases" link dhclient.leases.doc/Main} - DHCP client leases database

 MOSNet distribution also contains a DHCP server and relay agent. They are placed in a separate MOSNet-Server
package.

@endnode
@node control-panels "Using MiamiDeluxe control panels"

 MOSNet is compatible with MiamiDeluxe control panels. However, the
installation procedure is a little different from MiamiDeluxe:

1. Put the panel library (#?.MiamiPanel) file into MOSNet/Panels directory.
2. Specify the panel name in General.config file in "GUI PANEL".
3. If the panel has some additional files, put them into their original
   destination. For example, GelbesPanel requires to copy Images directory to
   MOSNet/Images and gelbespanel.gui file to MOSNet/Libs. Probably you'll also
   have to add Miami: assign to MOSNet directory (again, GelbesPanel requires
   this).
4. If you want the panel to be opened upon MOSNet startup, specify OPENGUI=YES
   in the general.config. If you set this parameter to NO the panel will not
   open on startup, however you'll be able to open it later using "Show" button
   in Commodoties Exchange.

 The following parameters in General.config affect the GUI:
   GUI PANEL
   GUI FONT
   OPENGUI
   REFRESH
   SHOW SPEED
   SHOW RATE
   SHOW UPTIME
   SHOW BYTES
   SHOW IFCONTROL
   SHOW GUICONTROL

 See @{"general.config description" link config-general} for detailed explanation
of these options.

 MOSNet is currently bundled with only one control panel called @{"MUI.MiamiPanel" link MUI.MiamiPanel.guide/Main}. It is completely
adapted to MOSNet environment and doesn't need any tweaks described here like Miami:
assign.

@endnode
@node service-scripts "Using service scripts"

 MOSNet supports running scripts for starting and stopping external network services
similar to those which can be found in UNIX operating systems.

 A standard place for scripts is MOSNet/db/rc.d directory. Used scripts are listed
in the @{"netdb file" link config-netdb} (an example is supplied with the default
installation) in the manner like:

RC rc.d/rc.samba
RC rc.d/rc.httpd

 In fact the line after "RC" is AmigaDOS command which is executed in order to run
the script. If you wish you can place the script everywhere else, you'll just need
to specify correct path to it, for example:

RC S:MyNetworkServices/samba.script

 These scripts will be executed upon MOSNet startup after the configuration is
complete and all interfaces configured as "UP" are online with "start" word as
an argument (i.e "rc.d/rc.samba start"). The order of execution is the same as
order in which you list them in the netdb file. The scripts are ran synchronously
and all of them must return. Normally you should use "Run" command inside scripts
in order to start server binaries.

 Upon quit these scripts will be called in reverse order with "stop" word as an
argument (i.e. "rc.d/rc.samba stop").

 These scripts are not necessary AmigaDOS shell script. You can use any
language you wish, for example Perl, Rexx or UNIX shell. You'll just need to specify
the interpteter like:

RC perl rc.d/rc.samba.pl

 Also the interpreter can be specified in the first line of the script as a comment
like you do normally, for example Rexx script can begin with "/*SYS:Rexxc/Rx */" and
UNIX shell scripts - with "#!/bin/sh" (only MorphOS recognizes it).

 When the script is called home directory will be MOSNet/db.

@endnode
@node config-general "general.config file"

 general.config is the master configuration file of MOSNet. It is loaded first and contains
vital parameters which the kernel needs to know before loading any modules and @{"network database" link config-netdb}.
 Changing this file may affect your system's performance or even functioning so please read
this section carefully and clearly understand what are you going to do if you want to change
some setting.

 This file consists of records whose generic form is:

 <Option name>=<Value>

 Option name can consist of one or two words. If there are aliases specified then any
of words can be replaced by an alias in any conbination. For example if there's
"MBUF_CONF INITIAL" option with "MBC I" alias, it's also valid to write "MBUF_CONF I" or
"MBC INITIAL".
 For boolean parameters you can specify "YES", "1" or "ON" for positive answer, any of
these values is correct. Negative answer can be specified as "NO", "0" or "OFF".

 For some names aliases are specified. Aliases may exist for both group and option names.

 The following options are supported:

 Network-related configuration options.

 These options specify some basic networking settings which don't fit into the
@{"network database" link config-netdb}.

GATEWAY=<Boolean>
   Switch gateway (router) functionality (also known as IP forwarding) on and off.
   Alias: GTW
   Default value: OFF

HOSTNAME=<string>
   Specify local lost name.
   Default value: empty, the hostname will be resolved from your local IP.

IPSENDREDIRECTS=<Boolean>
    Whether IP protocol should send ICMP redirect messages when the machine is
    used as a wrong gateway and forwards the received packet back to the same
    interface.
    Alias: REDIR
    Default value: ON

USELOOPBACK=<Boolean>
   Use the local loopback device (lo0) for local traffic.
   Alias: ULO
   Default value: ON

USENAMESERVER=NO|FIRST|SECOND
   How to use name server:
     NO     Do not use name server at all.  Local database will be used instead.
     FIRST  Query thename servers first and if that fails, use local database.
     SECOND First look up the local database, then, if that fails, query the name
	    servers.
   Alias: USENS
   Default value: SECOND

 Control panel configuration options.

 These options define the behavour of the control panel. These options are the most
frequently changed ones.

GUI FONT=<string>
   Specify font name in general AmigaOS format (like "Topaz/8") to be used by the
   panel.
   Default value: empty, behaviour depends on the panel itself.

   This option is actually deprecated because all modern software (and control panels)
   use MUI and their appearance is entirely controlled by the MUI preferences program.
   Such panels will simply ignore this option. It is effective only for some old non-MUI
   panels.

GUI PANEL=<string>
   Specify GUI panel library name. If you omit this parameter or set it to empty
   string the whole GUI engine will be disabled.
   Default value: empty, GUI disabled.

OPENGUI=<Boolean>
   Whether or not to open GUI on startup.
   Default value: ON

REFRESH=<number>
   Specify GUI panel information refresh perion in seconds.
   Default value: 1

SHOW SPEED=<Boolean>
   Whether or not the panel will display interfaces' speed
   Default value: ON

SHOW RATE=<Boolean>
   Whether or not the panel will display interfaces' current transfer rate
   Default value: ON

SHOW UPTIME=<Boolean>
   Whether or not the panel will display interfaces' uptime
   Default value: ON

SHOW BYTES=<Boolean>
   Whether or not the panel will display interfaces' transferred bytes count
   Default value: ON

SHOW IFCONTROL
   Whether or not the panel will display "On" and "Off" buttons for interfaces
   Default value: ON

SHOW GUICONTROL=<Boolean>
   Whether or not the panel will display its control buttons (Close, Quit, etc)
   Default value: ON

 Debugging options.

 You can use them in order to try to get some additional information
in the syslog about problems you have. Usually a developer may ask you to turn on one
of these options in order to research your bug report.

DEBUGSANA=<Boolean>
   Switch the SANA-II device interface debugging on and off.
   Alias: DBSANA
   Default value: OFF

DEBUGICMP=<Boolean>
   Switch the ICMP protocol debugging on and off.
   Alias: DBICMP
   Default value: OFF

DEBUGIP=<Boolean>
   Switch logging of the IP protocol debugging information on and off.
   Alias: DBIP
   Default value: OFF

 Logging subsystem configuration.
 
 The logging subsystem uses a fixed number of memory buffers with fixed
length to exchange log messages with the syslog viewer and file logging
process. Dynamic allocation of buffers is avoided in order to make the
processing more efficient. When a program tries to put a next message
into the syslog it will take a next free buffer and use it. If there are
no buffers availible the program will wait until one of them becomes free
(this can happen if your system generates high amount of logging information).
These waits will cause performance drop and you can use LOG COUNT parameter
in order to compensate this.

LOG COUNT=<Number>
   Number of log messages buffers to use. Increase this if your system generates
   high amount of logging data. However this increases memory usage.
   Default value: 5

LOG LEN=<Mumber>
   Maximum length of a log message in character. Increase this if some of your
   programs generate long messages which appear trimmed in the syslog.
   Default value: 128

LOG FILTERFILE=<number>
   Specify maximum log level for messages which are written to the log file:
     0 - Emergency
     1 - Alert
     2 - Critical
     3 - Error
     4 - Warning
     5 - Notice
     6 - Info
     7 - Debug
   Default value: 6

LOGFILENAME=<string>
   Specify the log file name.
   Default value: PROGDIR:Log/Syslog

 Memory buffers management subsystem configuration.

 These options control the heart of the stack - the memory management subsystem.

MBUF_CONF INITIAL=<Number>
   Number of mbuf chunks to allocate initially.
   Alias: MBC I
   Default value: 2

MBUF_CONF CHUNK=<Number>
   Number of mbufs to allocate at a time.
   Alias: MBC CH
   Default value: 64

MBUF_CONF CLCHUNK=<Number>
   Number of clusters toallocate at a time.
   Alias: MBC CL
   Default value: 4

MBUF_CONF MAXMEM=<Number>
   Maximum memory to use (in kilobytes).
   Alias:  MBC MM
   Default value: 1024

MBUF_CONF CLUSTERSIZE=<Number>
   Size of an mbuf cluster.
   Alias: MBC CS
   Default value: 2048

 Data transfer controlling options.

 These are two options affecting memory usage by the TCP protocol. Changing
them affects stack's performance. It's not necessary that increasing them gives
faster transfer rate, you need to find your optimal value experimentally.

TCP_SENDSPACE=<Number>
   Default size of the sending socket buffer in bytes for the TCP protocol.
   Alias: TCPSND
   Default value: 8192

TCP_RECVSPACE=<Number>
   Default size of the receiving socket buffer in bytes for the TCP protocol.
   Alias: TCPRCV
   Default value: 8192

 Operating system interaction options.

 Currently there's only one option in this group. It's AmiTCP legacy and
probably will be removed.

TASKNAME=<String>
  Name of the main stack's task.
  Defailt value: bsdsocket.library

 The whole general.config file is AmiTCP legacy. In future versions of MOSNet it will slowly
become deprecated and be replaced with standard BSD sysctl mechanism integrated
into the network database.

@endnode
@node config-netdb "Network database"

 The network database is the place where all the information about local hosts,
networks and services is stores. The network database is placed in the MOSNet/db/netdb
file. This file may consist of different types of records, include statements, script
statements and comments.

 A comment is everything which starts from "#" or ";". Everything beginning from one of these
characters and ending at the end of line is ignored.

 A MOSNet network database is very flexible, it allows you to store data in many different forms.
You can either have different kinds of data in different files or merge everything into one file.
A common case of multi-file configuration is supplied with the default MOSNet installation and is
a copy of network database files found in any UNIX system. This means that you can directly copy
the configuration of any UNIX host to your Amiga system.

 A record consists of a prefix and record body. A prefix is a keyword which specifies record type.
Record body format depends on what kind of record it is. The following prefixes exist (if a short
alias is availible then the prefix is described in the form PREFIX=ALIAS):

 INTERFACE=I   - an @{"interface record" link config-interfaces}
 HOST=H        - a @{"host record" link config-hosts}
 NET=N         - a @{"network record" link config-networks}
 SERVICE=S     - a @{"service record" link config-services}
 PROTOCOL=P    - a @{"protocol record" link config-protocols}
 NAMESERVER=NS - a @{"name server record" link config-nameservers}
 DOMAIN=DO     - a @{"domain name record" link config-domains}
 ROUTE=R       - a @{"route record" link config-routes}
 ACCESS=ACC    - an @{"access control record" link config-firewall}
 RC            - a @{"service script record" link service-scripts}

 Here is an example of several different records:

I eth0 DEV=DEVS:networks/via_rhinepci.device UNIT=0 IP=192.168.0.1 NETMASK=255.255.255.0 UP
H 127.0.0.1          localhost
H 192.168.0.1        sonic.home.net sonic
N loop	127	loopback
P ip   0
P icmp 1
P tcp  6
P udp  17
P raw  255

 An include statement has a form:

WITH <file name> [PREFIX=<entry type>]

 It tells to include an information from the specified file into the network database. An optional
prefix (one of described before) can be specified which tells that all entries in the file have
this type. If the prefix is specified then the file must contain only bodies of records, without
prefixes. It makes it possible to use UNIX-compatible configuration where different kinds of records
are stored in different files, one per file. Here is an example of NetDB file which implements
UNIX-compatible configuration model supplied with standard installation of MOSNet:

WITH interfaces PREFIX=I
WITH hosts PREFIX=H
WITH networks PREFIX=N
WITH protocols PREFIX=P
WITH services PREFIX=S
WITH static-routes PREFIX=R
WITH resolv.conf
WITH inet.access PREFIX=ACC

 Note that resolv.conf in this example doesn't have a prefix because it contains records of two
types (NAMESERVER and DOMAIN).

 Records of types I, R, R, ACC and RC are specific to MOSNet and don't have UNIX counterparts.

@endnode
@node config-interfaces "Interface records"

 Interface records define network interfaces. An interface is a physical connection to the network
via some device (networking card, modem, etc). These records specify mappings from interface names
(like eth0) to device driver name, unit number and other attributes.

 In a standard setup interface records are stored in "interfaces" file however you can change this
in @{"netdb" link config-netdb} file.

 Note that "lo0" interface is created within MOSNet automatically, you don't need to specify a
database record for it.

 Comments start with "#" or ";" and they continue to the end of the line.

 An interface entry has the following format:

     <interface name> DEVICE|DEV=<device name> UNIT=<unit number> [IP=<ip address>|DHCP] [NETMASK=<netmask>] [UP] [<advanced options>]

 Each field is described below:

 interface name
     The name for this network interface. This must be unique. Every interface in MOSNet is referred
   to by this name. You can choose any name you wish. UNIX specialists may choose names they've
   got used to (like "eth0"), but it can be also for example "LAN" or "Realtek". There are no
   enforced rules for this name in MOSNet.

 device name
     The name of the Sana-II device driver including the full path.

 unit number
     The physical unit number to be used with the Sana-II device.

 ip address
     The IP address for the interface to be configured statically. If you specify a magic string "DHCP"
   as the value then the interface will be completely configured by @{"DHCP" link dhcp}. NETMASK
   parameter is ignored in this case.

 netmask
     The netmask for the interface to be configured statically. Will be ignored if no IP address is
   specified.

 UP
     This is the switch telling MOSNet to bring the interface up (to online state) automatically.
   if you don't specify this the initial interface state will be offline. This is useful for example
   for defining modem connections which need to be brought up on demand.

 There are also a number of advanced options which can be used to finetune the interface. Usually
a SANA-II driver sets them to reasonable defaults, however if you are an expert you can use them
in order to get some special behaviour.
 Please do not change them if you don't exactly know what you're doing.

 POINT2POINT
     Set the interface to point-to-point mode. The interface will get POINTTOPOINT flag and will not
   process broadcasting packets.

 NOARP
     Disable ARP protocol for this interface (set NOARP flag). Normally, this flag is set for
   point-to-point interfaces. Note that ARP is necessary for broadcast mediums like Ethernet. Such
   interfaces will not work without it.

 IPREQUESTS=<number of requests>
     Number of IO requests to allocate for receiving IP packets. This option may affect stack's
   performance. Increase it for systems with high traffic load. Of course this increases memory
   usage.

 ARPREQUESTS=<number of requests>
     Number of IO requests to allocate for receiving ARP packets. Doesn't have any true impact on
   anything since it's hard to suggest some case with very high ARP traffic. Exists mainly for
   completeness.

 WRITEREQUESTS=<number of requests>
     Number of IO requests to allocate for transmitting the packets. The same rules as for
   IPREQUESTS are applied.

 ADDRESS=<hardware address>
     Hardware address used by Sana-II device configuration in hexadecimal notation with bytes
   separated by colons, e.g. "08:00:13:AE:45:EF". This should be used if your ethernet
   adapter has no address ROM, for example, or you've got two adapters with the same address for
   some strange reason.

 NOTRACKING
     Disable the packet type tracking on the Sana-II device in question.
   This feature is needed to circumvent a bug in a2060.device V37.2.

 IPTYPE=<type number>
     Packet type for the Internet Protocol (IP).

 ARPTYPE=<type number>
     Packet type for the Address Resolution Protocol (ARP).

 NOSIMPLEX
     Disable the copying of broadcast packets.  This parameter should be
   given if the broadcasts sent through the Sana-II driver are
   received on the sending machine as well.  Normally this is not the
   case, so this option should not normally be used.

 LOOPBACK
     Marks the interface as a loopback interface (sets LOOPBACK flag for it).
   This might be needed only in some rare testing cases.

 Here is a short example of "interfaces" file:

eth0 DEV=DEVS:networks/via_rhinepci.device UNIT=0 IP=192.168.0.1 NETMASK=255.255.255.0 UP
eth1 DEV=DEVS:networks/rtl_8139pci.device UNIT=0 IP=DHCP UP

 In this configuration two devices are defined: eth0 with static address 192.168.0.1 and netmask
255.255.255.0 and eth1 with dynamic configuration.
         
@endnode
@node config-hosts "Host records"

 Host records contain information about mapping host names to network addresses.
They can be used for example for small local network where you don't want to install
DNS service in order to make all computers accessible by name, or to specify some
frequently used or important hosts in order to make them accessible if you experience
DNS failure.

 In a standard setup host records are stored in "hosts" file however you can change this
in @{"netdb" link config-netdb} file.

 A host record has the following format:

 <Internet address> <official host name> <aliases>

 Items are separated by any number of blanks and/or tab characters.  A "#" indicates the
beginning of a comment; characters up to the end of the line are ignored. Network addresses
are specified in the conventional "." (dot) notation. Host names may
contain any printable character other than a field delimiter, newline, or comment character.

 Note that default domain names specified in @{"domain name records" link config-domains} don't have
any effect on resolving names via hosts records. Automatic domain name appending doesn't occur
here.

 For normal TCP stack operation the following minimal information must be specified:

 - a mapping of 127.0.0.1 address to "localhost" name;
 - a mapping of your primary interface address to your actual host name
   specified in @{"general.config" link config-general} in case of static configuration.

 Without this minimal information the stack can mailfunction.

 Here is an example of a "hosts" file containing three records:

127.0.0.1          localhost
192.168.0.1        sonic.home.net sonic
192.168.0.2        nata.nome.net  nata

 This assumes that your computer is named sonic.home.net and has IP address 192.168.0.1. Also
you can see a specification of an address 192.168.0.2 for some second computer in the local
network called nata.home.net. Additionally this file includes short aliases in order to prevent
the user from typing ".home.net" every time - this is a usual practice for accessing computers
in your own domain.

@endnode
@node config-networks "Network records"

 Network records contain information regarding the known networks which
comprise the DARPA Internet.

 In a standard setup network records are stored in "networks" file however you can change this
in @{"netdb" link config-netdb} file.

 A network record has the following format:

 <official network name> <network number> <aliases>

 Items are separated by any number of blanks and/or tab characters.  A "#" indicates the
beginning of a comment; characters up to the end of the line are ignored. Network numbers
may be specified in the conventional "." (dot) notation. Network names may contain any
printable character other than a field delimiter, newline, or comment character.

 For normal TCP stack operation this file must contain a mapping of number 127 to "loop" name with
"loopback" alias. Here is an example:

loop	127	loopback

 In a common practice network numbers are used rarely so usually you don't need to make any changes
in this information.

@endnode
@node config-protocols "Protocol records"

 Protocol records contain information regarding the known protocols.

 In a standard setup protocol records are stored in "protocols" file however you can change this
in @{"netdb" link config-netdb} file.

 A protocol record has the following format:

 <official protocol name> <protocol number> <aliases>

 Items are separated by any number of blanks and/or tab characters. A "#" indicates the
beginning of a comment; characters up to the end of the line are ignored. Protocol names
may contain any printable character other than a field delimiter, newline, or comment character.

 By default supplied "protocols" file contains all the information about supported protocols. It
can be used by various system diagnostics tools and MOSNet components themselves (like DHCP client
and server). Do not change it if you don't exactly know what you are doing and why. Here is an
example of a "protocols" file which comes with the default MOSNet installation:

ip   0
icmp 1
tcp  6
udp  17
raw  255

@endnode
@node config-routes "Static route records"

 These records define ways for the packets to travel from your machine to the outside world, in
particular - to the Internet.

 In a standard setup route records are stored in "static-routes" file however you can change this
in @{"netdb" link config-netdb} file.

 A route record has the following format:

 HOST|[NET] [DEST] <destination>|DEFAULT GATEWAY|GW <gateway>

 Items are separated by any number of blanks and/or tab characters. A "#" indicates the
beginning of a comment; characters up to the end of the line are ignored.

 Here is what the fields mean:

 HOST or NET specify whether the destination address presents a single host or a network. NET keyword
is optional, it is assumed by default.

 destination
   This is the destination IP address. In case of network destination this is a network address where
  all trailing zeros represent a host part and are ignored. For example NET 128.32 means "all hosts
  in a network 128.32.0.0/255.224.0.0". A keyword DEFAULT can be specified instead of an address here,
  in this case this record specifies a default gateway - an address where all the packets with unknown
  destination go. Usually this address is given to you by your Internet provider.

 gateway
   This is the gateway's IP address.

 An example:

NET 192.168.1.0 GATEWAY 192.168.0.1
HOST 192.168.2.2 GATEWAY 192.168.1.5
DEFAULT GATEWAY 128.65.2.10

 In this example you have another subnet on your local network (this assumes your network is 192.168.0.0),
one special host hidden behind 192.168.1.5 machine (connects to it via PPP) and an Internet connection with
gateay at 128.65.2.10 (this assumes you use a second interface to connect to the Internet).

 This example is an advanced case. In the simplest case you will have only one entry for default gateway.
You can also have no route records at all if you use DHCP or your host is connected to a single isolated
network (a very rare case).

 Remember that normally you can specify only one default gateway. If you specify several ones the first
definition will be used. The same applies to other systems, even to Microsoft Windows. There is simply
no way to have several default gateways, this is due to how the routing works in general. Ability to
specify several gateways in Windows and specify different gateways for different interfaces in Windows is
a misdesign, this will never work correctly.

@endnode
@node config-services "Service records"

 Service records contain information regarding the known services available in the Internet.

 In a standard setup service records are stored in "services" file however you can change this
in @{"netdb" link config-netdb} file.

 A service record has the following format:

 <official service name> <port number>/<protocol name> <aliases>

 Items are separated by any number of blanks and/or tab characters. The port number and protocol
name are considered a single item; a "/" is used to separate the port and protocol (e.g. "512/tcp").
A "#" indicates the beginning of a comment; subsequent characters up to the end of the line are ignored.
Service names may contain any printable character other than a field delimiter, newline, or comment
character.

 This information is used by various network diagnostics utilities in order to translate port number into
mnemonic service name. The more entries you have the better. Also it is used by inetd super-server
in order to determine port numbers which it listens at.

 Here is an example of a small "services" file consisting of some records:

echo		7/tcp
echo		7/udp
discard		9/tcp		sink null
discard		9/udp		sink null
systat		11/tcp		users
daytime		13/tcp
daytime		13/udp
netstat		15/tcp

@endnode
@node config-resolver "resolv.conf file"

 resolv.conf is a standard configuration file containing resolver settings. The resolver is a component of a
TCP/IP stack which provides lookup of an IP address by host name and vice versa. 

 In MOSNet the resolver is controlled by two kind of database records: @{"domain name records" link config-domains} and
@{"name server records" link config-nameservers}

 This file is also referred to by @{"netdb" link config-netdb} file.

@endnode
@node config-domains "Domain name records"

 Domain name records specify default domain names. Most queries for names within these domains
can use short names relative to them. In fact when you try to look up some name
without domain part (a short name is a name without any dots, e.g. "sonic") MOSNet will query
for this name with every default domain name appended until it's found.

 An example:

 Let us have the following domain name records:

DOMAIN foo.com
DOMAIN bar.net

 When we try to look up short host name "sonic" (e.g. enter "http://sonic" in the browser's URL gadget)
then the resolver will first query the nameserver for "sonic.foo.com" and then (if it's not found) for
"sonic.bar.net". If this fails too we'll get "Host not found" error.

 Despite it's simplicity this feature should be used with care. It's strongly adviced to specify only
local domains (to which your local network belongs) names in which are resolved by DNS server placed directly
on your network. If you specify some other domain (e.g. "com") you can experience severe perfomance loss
despite that you'll be able to reach pegasosppc.com just by typing "pegasosppc" for example because querying
remote name servers (responsible for .com domain in this example) every time introduces significant delay.
Specifying a nonexisting domain introduces a very large delay until all name server queries for this domain
time out.

 If you don't know your local domain names or don't have ones, just remove all domain name records from your
configuration. Don't invent nonexisting domains. Your short host name specified in  @{"general.config" link config-general}
must resolve to your own IP address with either local DNS server or your hosts records.

@endnode
@node config-nameservers "Name server records"

 A name server record specifies internet address (in dot notation) of a name server that the
resolver should query. If there are multiple servers specified, the resolver queries them in
the order listed. The algorithm used is to try a name server, and if the query times out, try
the next, until out of name servers, then repeat trying all the name servers until a maximum
number of retries are made.

 A short example:

NAMESERVER 202.15.195.3

@endnode
@node config-firewall "Access control records"

 MOSNet currently implements a very simple firewall (access control system) for TCP protocol.
You can deny incoming TCP connections on any port, in this case the remote end just receives the
usual "connection refused" error message. You can also log some defined connections.

 Access control records are used to set up this firewall. They have the following format:

 <service> <host address>[/<mask>] <access> [LOG]

 The fields are separated by blanks (spaces or tabs). Lines starting with either "#" or ";" character
are comments. Fields meaning is described below:

 service
     This is the port which this record affects. The value can be given as a port number, a service name
   defined in a @{"service record" Link "config-services"}, "*", "@", or "$". "*" means "every port",
   "@" - every privileged port (privileged are ports 1-1023), and "$" means "every service port"
   (ports 1-1023 and 5000-9999).

 host address
     This field describes which hosts this access control record affects. This is the host's IP address
   in the dot notation. Host names cannot be used here, since possible name server lookups could add
   unbearable delay to the process of connection acceptance. Multiple hosts can be covered by the same
   entry if you replace some parts of the address with "*".  The meaning of the "*" here is "any number".
   Thus the address parts replaced by "*" are not considered significant when doing address comparisons.

 mask
     A mask can be provided to cover more that one host with one entry. This is similar to the "*" part
   on the host address, but gives more precise control of the address comparison. It
   defines which bits on the host address are significant during the address comparison.

 access
     This field must contain either "allow" or "deny@", for the matching
   connection request to be accepted or dropped, respectively.

 LOG
     If this keyword is included, each connection request matching
   with this entry will be logged to AmiTCP/IP log despite of whether it is dropped or accepted.

 An example access control list:

finger   127.0.0.1              allow     LOG     ; 1
*        130.233.*.*            allow             ; 2
nntp     130.233.0/255.252.0.0  allow     LOG     ; 3
\@        *.*.*.*                deny              ; 4
*        *.*.*.*                allow     LOG     ; 5

 This list tells that:

 1. "finger" queries from local host are to be logged.
 2. All connections from hosts whose addresses start with 130.233 are to be allowed.
 3. Hosts on a bit wider set of class B-networks can access nntpd server of this host, and these
    connections will be logged.
 4. Connections to any of the remaining privileged ports are to be
    disallowed.
 5. Rest of the connection requests will be allowed and this activity will be logged.  Without this line
    these connections would be accepted silently, since that would be the default operation if no
    matches were found.

 The last 2 lines in the example are quite useful. If connection requests to all remaining ports (after
the line 3 in the example) would be denied, any local FTP clients would not work.  This is because the
FTP protocol normally requires the client to accept the data connection created for the file transfer.
The port number used is outside of the privileged port range, however. To guard all of your servers, it is
normally enough to restrict access to the privileged ports.  Some non-standard services which use
non-privileged ports, such as NetFS and IRC could be access controlled with port-specific entries in this
access control list.

 This simple firewall is AmiTCP legacy. In future versions of MOSNet it will be replaced by fully functional
BSD firewall.

@endnode
@node faq "MOSNet FAQ"

Q: I try to start some service using inetd. Why doesn't it work?
A: inetd is a separate program by itself and its porting is out of the scope of
   current task. You can use inetd from AmiTCP/Genesis package or try some 3rd
   party builds (from Louise for example).

Q: How to disable writing Logs/Syslog.txt?
A: Add LOGFILENAME=NIL: to the @{"general.conf" link config-general} file.

Q: I want more documentation (on AREXX interface, configuration files, etc).
A: Download file named AmiTCP-txt-20.lha. It is very old but contains many
   important information about AmiTCP (and MOSNet) which disappeared from newer
   releases. Also you can @{"report to authors" link support} about what kind of information you miss.
   However please don't expect immediate documentation update since the amount of
   needed work is really huge. Updating the documentation, however, depends on
   kind and amount of such requests.

Q: I rebooted from Linux to MorphOS and networking doesn't work. I can't ping any
   machine on the network except my one.
A: This is a well known problem having nothing to do with the network stack. This
   happens because newer Linux kernels put Rhine chip into sleep (power saving)
   mode upon shutdown. MorphOS driver should power up the chip back but it
   currently doesn't do it. There is a small tool by Fab called via-wakeup which
   solves this problem, run it from your S:User-Startup file before the network
   stack.
   The same relates to OpenFirmware which refuses to boot up from network if the
   machine was rebooted from Linux. There's no fix for the firmware availible.
   The only workaround is to power off the machine completely (disconnect its
   power cable) for 5 - 10 seconds.

Q: Host name resolving works slowly.
A: You've misconfigured the stack. First check your @{"default domain records" link config-domains} in the
   network database (resolv.conf) file. Then check your hostname and its @{"mapping to an IP address" link config-hosts}.

@endnode
@node history "Version history"

v1.2  - kernel:
	- Fixed memory trashing when closing TCP connection.
      - CLI environment:
	- netstat utility updated to FreeBSD v2.0.5 too and works again.
      - SDK:
	- Reorganized directories, now really fits for unarchiving directly into GG:
	  on MorphOS.
v1.1  - kernel:
	- TCP and UDP protocol code upgraded to FreeBSD v2.0.5, added support for T/TCP
	  protocol and dynamic TCP window sizing; SO_REUSEPORT option is implemented;
        - Improved service scripts starting mechanism;
      - documentation:
	- Added better documentation in AmigaGuide format;
	- DHCP suite documentation converted to readable plain text format;
      - DHCP suite:
	- omshell binary moved to server package since it relates to dhcpd and not dhclient.
v1.0  - kernel:
	- Changed default TCP buffer size back to 8192.
	- Improved compatibility with Envoy, now MOSNet will not set the SANA-II
	  device to the offline state together with the interface if it is also
          opened by someone else.
	- Added some error reports in the syslog about unimplemented features.
v0.19 - kernel:
	- Changed default TCP buffer size to 2048.
	- Added support for RC scripts.
	- Fixed bug: netmask specified in Interfaces file was actually ignored,
	  wrong mask was used for the route to the interface.
	- Fixed bug: syslog messages with any facility code set were ignored.
	- Fixed bug: random value was passed to dhclient as an stdout handler.
      - CLI environment:
	- Added "logger" tool.
v0.18 - kernel:
	- Fixed memory leak in the resolver.
	- Removed default RES_DNSRCH, resolver's performance improved.
	- Doesn't call sana_up() if the interface is already up.
	- Interfaces definition is moved from separate file to netdb.
	  IP address, netmask and initial online state are now also set there.
	- Added support for defining initial routing table in the NetDB.
	- Added support for MiamiDeluxe-compatible control panels as a GUI.
	- Added Commodities Exchange interface.
	- Added GUI configuration options to the General.config file.
	- Changed default value of DEBUGSANA parameter to OFF.
	- Changed default value of USENAMESERVER parameter to SECOND.
	- Implemented Miami-compatible packet filter hooks support.
	- Fixed bringing up an interface if the SANA-II driver is already
	  put online by some another protocol stack (EnvoyFS for example).
	- Implemented counting read bytes for SANA-II interface.
	- Some functions moved from miami.library to the kernel, Roadshow
	  API compatibility concept introduced to be used on potential
	  AmigaOS4 and probably m68k ports.
      - miami.library:
	- Implemented if_nameindex(), if_nametoindex(), if_indextoname(),
	  if_freenameindex(), MiamiPFAddHook(), MiamiPFRemoveHook()
	  functions.
	- Added QueryInterfaceTagList() function.
	- AddDynNameServ() now checks for correct sa_family value.
	- Renamed ezTCPSetSysLogPort() function to SetSysLogPort().
      - CLI environment:
	- Fixed bug in ifconfig: SIOCSIFFLAGS ioctl was called twice.
      - Control panels:
	- MUI.MiamiPanel first introduced.
v0.17 - kernel:
	- Fixed horrible bug in GetSocketEvents(): D0 was used instead of A0 as
	  event	storage pointer.
	- soevent() now ignores sockets with SS_NOFDREF flag set.
	- Socket events mask is now copied during socket copy creation inside
	  listen().
	- sana_run() is not called repeatedly any more on every IP address change,
	  avoiding additional I/O request allocation overhead.
	- Fixed ARP table allocation/cleanup in SIOCSIFADDR processing, wrong
	  pointer was tested for IFF_NOARP.
	- Now prints unit number together with interface name in online/offline
	  log messages.
	- Reverted timer.device handling in kern_synch.c to original version in
	  attempt to increase performance.
	- Disabled some diagnostics code.
v0.16 - kernel:
	- Rewritten NetDB handling by the resolver, dynamic entries are completely
	  separated from the configuration.
	- Fixed UDP statistics gathering - dropped broadcast packets count is
	  separated from generic dropped packets count.
      - miami.library:
	- API for adding dynamic nameservers and domain names changed.
      - CLI environment:
	- netstat tool changed to reflect UDP statistics change in the kernel.
      - DHCP support:
	- Rewritten to use new API.
	- Fixed bug: added forgotten RTF_GATEWAY flag when adding route to default
	  gateway.
v0.15 - global:
	- Project renamed to MOSNet due to name collision (product named ezTCP
	  already exists).
      - miami.library:
	- Implemented some netdb manipulation functions.
	- Implemented sethostname() function.
      - usergroup.library:
        - Fixed stupid bug which led to wrong functions being called
        - Implemented group and passwd file handling
      - kernel:
        - Reverted back mbuf configuration to what it was in v0.13
	- Renamed AREXX port to "MOSNET".
	- Now maintains HOSTNAME environment variable
	- Improved socket events code, removed some problems with duplicated
	  sockets.
	- FD_ACCEPT event is now actually generated.
	- Added EZTCP_sethostname() function, provides support for miami.library/sethostname()
      - CLI environment:
        - Added "netstat" tool.
	- Added "hostname" tool.
	- Fixed address printout in "arp" tool.
      - DHCP support:
	- Implemented nameservers, hostname and domain mame options processing.
v0.14 - miami.library:
	- Rewritten MiamiIsOnline() to recognize local interfaces by IFF_LOOPBACK
	  flag instead of "lo" in the beginning of the name.
	- Added new functions: link_aton() and link_ntoa(), ezTCPResetNetDB().
	- Rewritten resolver control functions due to changed internal data
	  interchange.
      - kernel:
	- Changed default mbuf configuration.
	- Fixed potential crash in Dup2Socket() if destination socket is in use.
	- Tag (if present) is now printed properly in the syslog.
	- Now accepts netmasks smaller than default one.
	- Added support for AF_LINK addresses.
	- rtm_pid field in route messages is now filled in properly.
	- Added private tag exposing resolver state structure - for future
	  miami.library functions
	- Added support for SIOCGIFMTU and SIOCGIFINDEX ioctl's.
	- Added private EZTCP_FindKernelVar() function providing support for
	  libkvm used by netstat utility.
	- Fixed RESET ARexx command.
	- Added private EZTCP_ResetNetDB() function (provides support for
	  miami.library/ezTCPResetNetDB() ).
      - Syslog viewer:
	- Removed redundant "Save as..." operation from the menu.
      - CLI environment:
	- "ifconfig" utility upgraded.
      - DHCP support:
	- First introduced.

v0.13 - Documentation:
        - Added this file.
      - miami.library:
        - Implemented MiamiIsOnline() and MiamiOnOffline() - YAM works again.
        - MiamiOpenSSL() does not report "Function not implemented" any more.
      - CLI environment:
        - Updated "startnet" script.
        - Included new "stopnet" script.
      - Kernel:
        - Second attempt to fix packet fragmentation bug.
        - Fixed potential structure copy problem in SIOCGIFCONG ioctl code.
        - Changed ARexx port name to "EZTCP".
        - Added possibility to quit ezTCP with "BREAK PORT=EZTCP" command.
        - Fixed crash when kernel exits before syslog viewer.
      - Syslog viewer:
	- Fixed displaying of entries with non-empty process name - wrong color
	  was used.
        - Fixed color change.

v0.12 - Kernel:
	- Replaced IP fragmentation code with newer version from 4.4BSD in
	  attempt to fix unnecessary fragmentation bug.
      - miami.library:
	- First introduced.
      - Syslog viewer:
	- First introduced, CLI syslog window removed.
      - CLI environment:
        - New "startnet" script included.
      - usergroup.library:
	- Fixed crash on library close.

v0.11 - Changelog lost in time.

@endnode
@node future "Plans for future"

 What to expect in future versions of MOSNet:

 MOSNet can be developed in several major directions, each of them takes significant
amount of time and effort. There are lots of different goals which are developed under
different conditions.

 The following is a free work which will be performed by me:

 - Improved Miami and Roadshow compatibility;
 - Graphical configuration editor;
 - AROS port;

 The following tasks are large and need to be supported by some kind of donations or need
another developer to accomplish:

 - Native version of inetd and TCP: device;
 - PPP, PPPoE, PPTP support;
 - IPv6 support;
 - Support for other socket-based protocols (IrDA, may be IEEE1394);

 The following tasks are "nice to do" but currently there are no requests. May be someone
will like one of these ideas:

 - Complete code upgrade to recent NetBSD version;
 - Appletalk support;
 - Advanced packet filtering, firewalling;
 - IPX support (at least limited, enough for old games ported from MS-DOS);
 - More modularity (protocol modules separated from the rest of the kernel);
 - Built-in transparent proxy client.

 MOSNet is an open project and is ready to accept any ideas and/or suggestions. Any kind of
donations is appreciated and can affect speed and/or direction of the current development.

@endnode
@node support "Technical support"

 MOSNet is an opensource project and everyone can join it. However currently it's developed
only by me:

 Pavel Fedin <sonic_amiga@rambler.ru>

 MOSNet is a part of Unofficial MorphOS update project and is hosted at SourceForge:

 http://sourceforge.net/projects/unmorphos

 The technical support for MOSNet is availible mainly via the mailing list. Go to
http://www.freelists.org/list/mosnet for subscription. If you have problems with
the list please feel free to email me directly. Help also may be availible in
forums on MorphZone (http://morphzone.org).

@endnode
